that the South African legal system could be relied upon for justice. But when the courts failed to respond, he had no choice but to shift tactics, developing what would ultimately become his lasting legacy—the philosophy and practice of nonviolent civil disobedience. As he took on the most powerful governmental, economic, and political forces of his day, Gandhi transformed himself from a modest civil rights lawyer into a tireless freedom fighter. Relying on never-before-seen archival materials, this book provides the reader with a front-row seat to the dramatic events that would alter Gandhi—and history—forever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aEast IndiansxLegal status, laws, etc.zSouth AfricaxHistory. 0aLawyers -- India -- Biography. 0aLawyerszIndiavBiography. 0aLawyerszSouth AfricavBiography. 0aSouth Africa -- Politics and government -- 1836-1909. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aarchival materials.  abiographical.  abiography.  acareer.  acivic.  acultural anthropology.  adramatic events.  aearly years.  aengaging.  aequality.  aethical logic.  agandhi.  ahuman condition.  aindian civil rights movement.  aindian history.  ajustice.  alaw practice.  alegal system.  alife changes.  alucrative business.  anonviolent civil disobedience.  apage turner.  apersonal journey.  aphilosophical evolution.  apolitical forces.  apolitical.  arevolutionaries.  aself discovery.  asocial issues.  asouth africa.  awealthy indian merchants.  awhite colonial establishment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095662940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956629423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/978052095662